<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-324-178  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 324 178.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  June 5 1989 n420 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Erasable optical comes of age. (erasable optical disk technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Webb, Dave.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Rewritable optical disk technology is becoming feasible as anon-line mass-storage medium for workstations and as a part ofadd-on disk subsystems.andP;  Despite a four-year slow start, fivecompanies, mostly Japanese, have drives available.andP;  The presentgeneration of erasable drives are magneto-optic, blending magneticstorage with laser optic technology.andP;  Erasable optical storage wasfocused on in the fall of 1988 when Next Inc revealed that arewritable optical drive would be the main storage medium in itsworkstation.andP;  Analysts predict that 40,000 to 50,000 could beshipped in 1990, compared with 4000 to 5000 in 1989.andP;  The disk ishoused in a cartridge that can be removed and replaced.andP;  Dust thatcauses other storage mediums to crash and erase stored data is nota problem.andP;  Application potential for rewritable optical drives isvery broad, but they have slow access times and may not besuitable for everyone.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Erasable Optical MemoryNew ProductTrendsWorkstationsDisk DrivesMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Drives away. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>